I have two clusters in my euca setup(VMware and Xen). Xen is OK but VMware is creating this problem.\n\nI have created one post on engage: https://engage.eucalyptus.com/customer/portal/questions/575364-not-able-to-create-new-volumes-and-instances-for-a-particular-zone\n\n","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/user?username=nky1986","name":"nky1986","key":"nky1986","accountId":"557058:5e5bdf82-dccb-41a8-834b-ca20404905f1","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/a4ce4785a82711452b898c46461a86ec?s=48&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3FavatarId%3D10122%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","24x24":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/a4ce4785a82711452b898c46461a86ec?s=24&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dsmall%26avatarId%3D10122%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","16x16":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/a4ce4785a82711452b898c46461a86ec?s=16&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dxsmall%26avatarId%3D10122%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","32x32":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/a4ce4785a82711452b898c46461a86ec?s=32&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dmedium%26avatarId%3D10122%26noRedirect%3Dtrue"},"displayName":"narender yadav","active":false,"timeZone":"US/Central"},"created":"2012-10-19T07:52:27.698-0500","updated":"2012-10-19T07:52:27.698-0500"},{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/issue/14803/comment/34148","id":"34148","author":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/user?username=zhill","name":"zhill","key":"zhill","accountId":"557058:70b4b768-eb1f-43a3-a225-3353d0fe3f56","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/239165321c2f152424c9be883721791a?s=48&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3FownerId%3Dzhill%26avatarId%3D10406%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","24x24":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/239165321c2f152424c9be883721791a?s=24&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dsmall%26ownerId%3Dzhill%26avatarId%3D10406%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","16x16":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/239165321c2f152424c9be883721791a?s=16&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dxsmall%26ownerId%3Dzhill%26avatarId%3D10406%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","32x32":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/239165321c2f152424c9be883721791a?s=32&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3Fsize%3Dmedium%26ownerId%3Dzhill%26avatarId%3D10406%26noRedirect%3Dtrue"},"displayName":"Zach Hill","active":true,"timeZone":"America/Los_Angeles"},"body":"There are a few of issues at play here. First, it sounds like the DB is not quite accurate. Second, the accounting for Volume size limits is actually done using the volume storage statistics, which is not part of the DB and was intended to be deprecated long ago--the limit check should be against 'available'+'pending' volumes. Third, the error message is terrible both for the end-user and for the admin trying to diagnose the problem.\n\nActions: Fix the size-limit check to use the DB and to correctly account for pending volumes as well as extant ones. Fix the way the CLC handles failures returned from the SC such that it can possibly return an error to the end-user (it is unclear if that should be an explicit error on the run command or simply a failed volume), and make log messages in the SC legible such that the admin knows what is happening. For 3.2 onward this could include a fault-log messages found in sc-faults.log","updateAuthor":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/user?username=zhill","name":"zhill","key":"zhill","accountId":"557058:70b4b768-eb1f-43a3-a225-3353d0fe3f56","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/239165321c2f152424c9be883721791a?s=48&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3FownerId%3Dzhill%26avatarId%3D10406%26noRedirect%3Dtrue","24x24":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/239165321c2f1524